<DOC><DOCNO> AP880511-0259 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1834EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-11 0309</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0316</SECOND><HEAD>Heavy Rain In Texas, Hail in Florida, Maryland and Pennsylvania</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Thunderstorms dumped rain in Texas and pelted Florida, Marylandand Pennsylvania with hail Wednesday, while rain dampened much ofNew York and New England.   Sunny skies prevailed from the south Atlantic and Gulf Coaststates across the Ohio, Mississippi and Tennessee valleys toportions of the northern and central Plains. Skies were also sunnyfrom the Rockies to the West Coast.   Up to 2 inches of rain fell in parts of southwest Texas, causingsome local flooding. A severe thunderstorm watch was in effect fora large part of southern Texas.   The storms produced hail between Waldo and Green Cove Springs innorthern Florida and pea- to marble-size hail in central Marylandand eastern Pennsylvania.   Rain was widespread from eastern New York to most of NewEngland. The only section of New England to escape rain wasnorthern Maine.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDTincluded 1.38 inches at San Angelo, Texas; 0.49 inch at Midland,Texas; 0.47 inch at Bridgheport, Conn., and 0.46 inch at Hartford,Conn.   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EST ranged from 43 degrees at GrandMarais, Minn., to 104 at Thermal, Calif. The nation's morning lowwas 16 at Gunnison, Colo.   Thursday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms fromsouthern and eastern Texas to southern Mississippi; scatteredshowers over the Great Lakes, northern New York and northernVermont; rain over parts of Washington and Oregon, and sunshineover most of the remainder of the nation.   High temperatures were expected to reach the 70s and 80s acrossmost of the nation, with readings in the 60s in New England and NewYork, in the 50s and 60s from Michigan to eastern Minnesota, and inthe 90s to near 105 in the desert Southwest.</TEXT></DOC>